text: This is literally like the plot from the Metal Gear Solid games. A soldier called Big Boss (then codenamed Naked Snake) is sent to Russia to extract a rocket scientist, Nikolai Stepanovich Sokolov. He fails, then finds out his mentor betrays him and his country (yet it is revealed at the end that she was a spy and her mission was to defect; it was given to her by the United States Government). Naked Snake‚Äôs mission is to kill his mentor, The Boss, who‚Äôs like a mother to him, and extract the scientist. He completes his mission (killing his boss at the end) and is awarded the title, ‚ÄúBig Boss‚Äù. Big Boss starts his own organization called ‚ÄúMilitaires San Fronti√®res‚Äù in 1974. Two years earlier, his then-current unit FOX had stolen his DNA and made 3 clones of him: Solid Snake, Liquid Snake, and Solidus Snake. In the late 90‚Äôs Big Boss sends Solid Snake to Outer Heaven, to destroy a walking battle tank, Metal Gear. Solid Snake finds out that Big Boss is behind the whole thing, then kills him. Solid Snake is sent on another mission to Zanzibar Land a few years later, to destroy another Metal Gear and extract a scientist. At the end, Snake discovers that Big Boss was behind Zanzibar as well (the Big Boss killed in Outer Heaven was a Phantom), so he ‚Äúkills‚Äù him. In the early 2000s, Snake is sent to a nuclear disposal facility, Shadow Moses Island, in the Fox Archipelago. Solid Snake‚Äôs rival and the boss of the operation, Liquid Snake, uncovers to Snake at the end that Big Boss was their father, and that they were both clones. I can‚Äôt believe no one has realized this.

text: I was quite surprised at how good this movie is. The story isn't so much about the action as it is about a couple moral themes on facing yourself, in this case literally, dealing with the moral consequences of a death dealing lifestyle, and using those experiences to prevent the same corruption of someone else. On the flip side, while I think the ending for the bad guy should've been different, it did a great job of showing what happens to people when there's no real love from a father figure, only a distorted teaching of respect and reasoning. The structural consequential frailty of playing God is balanced out by the fact you can always change.....if you so choose. Key scenes do very good at raising emotions and questions, so I highly recommend this movie to anybody who likes smooth flowing thought provoking tales.

text: Now I‚Äôm certain Rotten Tomatoes et al are completely full of shit. I‚Äôm no Will Smith fan, and think most of what Hollywood produces is crap designed for sheep, so I went in w/ my teenage son expecting another round of mind numbing drivel, but by the 45 minute mark was pleasantly surprised. This is a well written, directed and acted movie, all the way through. Yes the plot line is fantastical, but it is carried out convincingly, and the relationships feel genuine, as does the action. Winstead combines a deep, natural beauty with an intelligent confidence, and never seems artificial as a government agent in harm‚Äôs way. And Will Smith plays the part just so; he has truly become a fine actor and that helps him transcend the action movie hero into someone relatable. The storyline never feels rushed, like most movies today appealing to the ADHD clientele they seemingly seek. I paid $10 for my ticket. Made out like a bandit.
